8.4. SolasSimu1 Data¶

This example notebook demonstrates how to use PiML in its low-code mode for testing fairness of machine learning models using the SolasSimu1 data. This is a simulated dataset, modified from the Friedman #1 regression problem. The covariates used for modeling are Segment, x1, x2, …, x5, the response Label is binary and it is a classification problem. The rest variables are demographic variables used for testing fairness. The data is contributed by Solas-AI.

8.4.1. Stage 0: Install PiML package on Google Colab¶

  1. Run !pip install piml to install the latest version of PiML

  2. In Colab, you’ll need restart the runtime in order to use newly installed PiML version.

8.4.2. Stage 1: Initialize an experiment, Load and Prepare data¶

[ ]:

from piml import Experiment
exp = Experiment()

[4]:

# Choose SolasSimu1
exp.data_loader()

[6]:

# Exclude these features one-by-one: "Minority", "Majority", "Age >= 62", "Age < 62" (demographic variables);
# Excluded features will show in grey color in the table.
exp.data_summary()

[7]:

# Prepare dataset with default settings
exp.data_prepare()

[8]:

# Choose XGB2 with default settings, click run;
# When training is finished, register the models one by one.
exp.model_train()

8.4.3. Stage 3. Fairness Testing via Solas-AI¶

  • First select a registered model, say XGB2,

  • Then In Group Setting Panel:

    • Set Add Category=“Weighted Group”, Enter “Race” in Category Name; Select “Majority” in reference; Select “Minority” in protected; Click on Add Button.

    • Set Add Category=“Weighted Group”, Enter “Age” in Category Name; Select “Age<62” in reference; Select “Age>=62” in protected; Click on Add Button.

  • Then Switch to the Metrics Panel:

    • Select a metric (default to AIR); Select the Threshold and Class for cutting the predicted response as favored or unfavored.

  • Then Switch to Segmented AIR:

    • Select the segment feature; Select the number of bins if it is a numerical feature; otherwise, it will be segmented automatically using its classes.

[9]:

exp.model_fairness()
